    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Take a look at <a href=\"http://ssw.jku.at/dcevm\" rel=\"noreferrer\">DCEVM</a>, it's a modification of the HotSpot VM that allows unlimited class redefinitions at runtime. You can add/remove fields and methods and change the super types of a class at runtime.</p>\n<p>The binaries available on the original site are limited to Java 6u25 and to early versions of Java 7. The project has been forked on <a href=\"https://github.com/dcevm/dcevm\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Github</a> and supports recent versions of Java 7 and 8. The maintainer provides binaries for 32/64 bits VMs on Windows/Linux. Starting with Java 11 the project moved to a new <a href=\"https://github.com/HotswapProjects/openjdk-jdk11-dcevm\" rel=\"noreferrer\">GitHub</a> repository and now also provides binaries for OS X.</p>\n<p>DCEVM is packaged for Debian and Ubuntu, it's conveniently integrated with OpenJDK and can be invoked with <code>java -dcevm</code>. The name of the package depends on the version of the default JDK:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Debian 7&amp;8 and Ubuntu 15.04 : <a href=\"https://packages.qa.debian.org/o/openjdk-7-jre-dcevm.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">openjdk-7-jre-dcevm</a></li>\n<li>Debian 9 and Ubuntu 16.04 : <a href=\"https://packages.qa.debian.org/o/openjdk-8-jre-dcevm.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">openjdk-8-jre-dcevm</a></li>\n<li>Debian 10 and Ubuntu 19.04 : <a href=\"https://packages.qa.debian.org/o/openjdk-11-jre-dcevm.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">openjdk-11-jre-dcevm</a></li>\n</ul>\n"
  }, {
